    "short_description": "Non-ferrous metal casting using the lost-wax casting technique, practiced by tribes in Bengal, Odisha, and Chattisgarh.",
    "long_description": "Dhokra is an ancient folk art tradition of non-ferrous metal casting. It uses the 'Lost Wax' casting (cire perdue) technique, one of the oldest known methods of metal casting (dating back to Mohenjo-Daro). \n\nThe artisans create a clay core, wrap it in beeswax threads to form the design, cover it with clay again, and then pour molten brass/bronze which melts and replaces the wax. The result is a rustic, primitive-looking metal figure, often measuring inches to a few feet.",
